                            <div class="columnGroup first">
                                <h1 itemprop="headline" class="articleHeadline">BOOKSHELF / /; Dig It</h1>
                                <h6 class="byline">
                                    <span itemprop="author creator" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <span itemprop="name">By MARIA RUSSO</span>
                                    </span>
                                </h6>
                                <h6 class="dateline">Published: May 10, 2015</h6>
                                <div class="shareTools shareToolsThemeClassic articleShareToolsTop" data-shares="facebook,twitter,google,email,showall|Share,print,singlepage,reprints,ad" data-title="BOOKSHELF / /; Dig It" data-url="https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D03E3D8143FF933A25756C0A9639D8B63"
                                    data-description="the potato kingWritten and illustrated by Christoph Niemann. 32 pp. Owlkids. $17.95. (Picture book; ages 3 to 8)&lt;p/&gt;"></div>
                                <meta name="emailThisHash" content="Qslnvaq5Mvj4h1XvBFFVrw">
                                <div class="articleBody">
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        the potato kingWritten and illustrated by Christoph Niemann. 32 pp. Owlkids. $17.95. (Picture book; ages 3 to 8)</p>
                                    <p> </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        It&#x2019;s a perfectly constructed legend, and it may well be true: A long-ago king called Fritz &#x2014; Frederick the Great to you and me &#x2014; imported a South American wonder crop: potatoes. He tried to get the people to eat them, to no avail.
                                        So he ordered his army to guard the fields, but not too closely. Thus enticed into stealing the spuds, his subjects fell in love with them, and have been planting them ever since. Niemann tells the tale with wonderful
                                        economy and, of course, delightful potato-print art. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        if you plant a seedWritten and illustrated by Kadir Nelson. 32&#x202F;pp. Balzer &amp; Bray. $18.99. (Picture book; ages 3 to 8)</p>
                                    <p> </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Nelson (&#x201C;Baby Bear,&#x201D;&#x2009; &#x201C;We Are the Ship&#x201D;) digs deep, as always, to remind us how things grow: Just as tomato and carrot seeds yield tomatoes and carrots, the seeds of selfishness bring &#x201C;a heap of trouble.&#x201D;
                                        Plant kindness and you get something &#x201C;very, very sweet.&#x201D; With Nelson&#x2019;s wondrous ground-level viewpoint and saturated colors, the illustrations show a rabbit and mouse tending crops and enjoying
                                        the haul, while a towering lineup of hungry birds look on, first for a food fight, then a happy feast. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        UP IN THE GARDEN AND DOWN IN THE DIRTBy Kate Messner. Illustrated by Christopher Silas Neal. 32&#x202F;pp. Chronicle. $16.99. (Picture book; ages 3 to 8) </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        The author-illustrator team behind &#x201C;Over and Under the Snow&#x201D; once again take a warmly multilayered approach in this idyllically rustic story. A girl and her hip grandmother work, watch and wait in their garden over the course of a year.
                                        All the while a panoply of creatures in the dirt do their own things to make the garden flourish. Neal&#x2019;s lovely, dusky art lavishes the same attention on a grasshopper as on the people, capturing a mood that&#x2019;s
                                        both languid and teeming with life. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Rosario&#x2019;s fig treeBy Charis Wahl. Illustrated by Luc Melanson. 32 pp. Groundwood. $16.95. (Picture book; ages 4 to 8) </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        Is it magic? Rosario &#x201C;knows the perfect day to put in every plant and seed&#x201D; in his garden, next door to the girl who narrates this story of cross-cultural neighborliness. His most astounding move involves a fig tree: He digs it up, then
                                        buries it underground for the winter. Replanted in spring, it bears fruit again. &#x201C;You just learn, and then you know,&#x201D; Rosario shrugs. Melanson&#x2019;s digital art has a charming oddness, capped by
                                        a witty scene of Rosario and his elderly Italian friends debating. </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        IN MARY&#x2019;S GARDENBy Tina and Carson K&#xFC;gler. 32 pp. Houghton Mifflin Harcourt. $16.99. (Picture book; ages 4 to 8)</p>
                                    <p></p>
                                    <p> </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        The Wisconsin outsider artist Mary Nohl, who died in 2001, makes a clever picture book subject. As a girl she was &#x201C;happiest when her hands were busy making, building, creating things.&#x201D; Later she hauled rocks, sea glass and found objects
                                        from a beach back to her cabin, where she put them on massive concrete animal figures. Soon her front yard was a zany sculpture garden that still attracts noisy visitors, an endnote says, annoying more conventional
                                        neighbors. Surely children will relate. </p>
                                    <p> </p>
                                    <p itemprop="articleBody">
                                        <block class="ils_text">
                                        </block>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        DRAWINGS: Clockwise from top left: &#x201C;The Potato King&#x201D;; &#x201C;Up in the Garden and Down in the Dirt&#x201D;; and &#x201C;Rosario&#x2019;s Fig Tree.&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>
                                        <br> </p>
                                </div>
